ñíŸ@397812caca900bf8ef5a0041bfc1c703e728baccbf6cc74c9fb1e87c7e852504⁄¶Title: title: ssh-agent
Path: Manage SSH passphrases
Content:
``eval``
 is not available in nushell, so run:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
^ssh-agent -c
    | lines
    | first 2
    | parse "setenv {name} {value};"
    | transpose -r
    | into record
    | load-env

```
::: warning

Adding this to your 
``env.nu``
 will however start a new ssh-agent process every time you start a new terminal.

See the workarounds.

:::
íŸ@4a8b8703de7a242829b096fc00a58398852c0e7f8f7bb796f285b615a92b5f96⁄DTitle: title: ssh-agent
Path: Workarounds
Content:
You can work around this behavior by checking if a ssh-agent is already running on your user, and start one if none is:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
do --env {
    let ssh_agent_file = (
        $nu.temp-dir | path join $"ssh-agent-(whoami).nuon"
    )

    if ($ssh_agent_file | path exists) {
        let ssh_agent_env = open ($ssh_agent_file)
        if ($"/proc/($ssh_agent_env.SSH_AGENT_PID)" | path exists) {
            load-env $ssh_agent_env
            return
        } else {
            rm $ssh_agent_file
        }
    }

    let ssh_agent_env = ^ssh-agent -c
        | lines
        | first 2
        | parse "setenv {name} {value};"
        | transpose --header-row
        | into record
    load-env $ssh_agent_env
    $ssh_agent_env | save --force $ssh_agent_file
}

```
íŸ@cd86f717c408ce8f310b1f6822623e7c4703ff50df2ba0b8cc88548a5408d503⁄VTitle: title: ssh-agent
Path: Keychain
Content:
[link: https://www.funtoo.org/Funtoo:Keychain] ```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
keychain --eval --quiet <your ssh keys, eg. id_ed25519>
    | lines
    | where not ($it | is-empty)
    | parse "{k}={v}; export {k2};"
    | select k v
    | transpose --header-row
    | into record
    | load-env

```
íŸ@7ab1dcb25a7c708eda436e2e971f65ce06a8dc2b55839ff7bfd2d5807c5075f3ŸıTitle: title: ssh-agent
Path: Non-nushell workarounds
Content:
However, the commonly recommended approach involves running an ssh-agent so it establishes an user-wide socket for processes to connect to.
Here are two common ways to achieve this.
íŸ@dcfbb7f3171649e111173932449e1c4c59632096e905fe4b8aaaf433e9f95ccd⁄«Title: title: ssh-agent
Path: DE/WM config
Content:
You can incorporate it into your Desktop Environment (DE) or Compositor's configuration using the following command:
```Fenced(Borrowed("sh"))
ssh-agent -D -a /run/user/1000/ssh-agent.socket
# You can also set this socket path as an environment variable using the same config file

```
This a good option for you if you're using a Windows Manager or a Compositor since you're likely to know its syntax.
íŸ@933f357e226bc69ec56c85cfa58cea35b226388be25adfc28679f3e0403f5651⁄êTitle: title: ssh-agent
Path: As a service
Content:
Alternatively, you can enable it as an 
user service
. OpenSSH typically includes a systemd service and the 
[link: https://wiki.archlinux.org/title/Systemd/User] ArchLinux wiki systemd/User
 page covers how to enable services per user with systemd.
However, if you're using a different service manager, please refer its own documentation to create a user service that utilizes the aforementioned command.
To enable Nushell to access this socket, you need to add its path as 
``$env.SSH_AUTH_SOCK``
 like so:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.SSH_AUTH_SOCK = $"($env.XDG_RUNTIME_DIR)/ssh-agent.socket"

```
